    explanation: 'CA.L3-3.12.2e requires that adversarial assessments be performed by independent teams — people not part of the organization\'s regular security function. The independence requirement addresses two distinct problems: (1) Organizational bias: internal teams have institutional knowledge that unconsciously steers testing away from sensitive areas, systems believed to be well-protected, or findings that would reflect poorly on past decisions. An independent team follows the threat model, not organizational politics. (2) Threat perspective: independent red teams bring external threat intelligence and do not have the implicit trust assumptions that come from working inside an organization. They approach the target as an adversary would — with no assumptions about what is defended.',
    mindsetNote: 'Independence is not primarily about technical skill — internal red teams can be highly skilled. It is about perspective and bias. An insider knows which systems "should" be protected and may unconsciously avoid testing them. An outsider knows only that CUI is the target and will follow every attack path to it regardless of organizational context. CA.L3-3.12.2e specifically calls for independence to ensure that adversarial assessments reflect realistic threat scenarios, not comfortable organizational assumptions.',
