    explanation: 'CA.L2-3.12.1 requires periodically assessing security controls to determine effectiveness. "Periodically" is not a fixed annual or triennial interval — it means the organization defines a frequency appropriate to its risk posture and reassesses when significant changes occur. A major network architecture change alters the operating environment in ways that may invalidate prior assessment findings. New attack surfaces, changed data flows, and modified trust boundaries all require reassessing the controls that depend on them. A static three-year cycle that ignores interim changes misses the intent of the practice.',
    mindsetNote: 'Security assessments are not calendar events — they are risk-driven. Trigger-based reassessment (significant change, new threat, incident, new system component) is as important as time-based reassessment. Assessors will ask not only "when was your last assessment?" but "what has changed since then and were those changes assessed?" The honest answer here is that 14 months of changes to the network architecture have not been evaluated.',
    sourceRef: 'NIST SP 800-171 Rev 2 §3.12.1',
