    explanation: 'AC.L2-3.1.14 requires routing all remote access through managed access control points — a centralized gateway that can inspect, log, and enforce policy on remote sessions before they reach internal resources. Direct VPN tunnels terminating at destination servers bypass the centralized inspection point. The managed access control point is where authentication, authorization, session logging, and traffic inspection occur. Without it, each server manages remote access independently, creating inconsistent enforcement and monitoring blind spots.',
    mindsetNote: 'Hub-and-spoke VPN (all traffic through a central concentrator) is preferred over direct device-to-device VPN for CUI environments. Zero-trust network access (ZTNA) solutions also satisfy this requirement. The key principle: remote access must pass through a choke point where policy is consistently applied and audited.',
    sourceRef: 'NIST SP 800-171 Rev 2 §3.1.14',
