    explanation: 'DFARS 252.204-7012(c) requires contractors who discover a cyber incident to rapidly report it to DoD. The reporting window is within 72 hours of discovery, and the designated mechanism is the DoD\'s DIBNet portal at dibnet.dod.mil. Phone or email notification to the contracting officer (A, C) does not satisfy this requirement — the DIBNet portal submission is the mandatory mechanism. DCSA notification (D) is an additional obligation for certain classified programs but does not replace the DIBNet report, and the 7-day timeline is incorrect. The 72-hour clock starts at discovery, not at the completion of the investigation.',
    mindsetNote: 'A critical misconception: many contractors believe they must complete their investigation before filing the report. DFARS does not require a completed investigation — it requires a rapid notification within 72 hours of discovery with what is known at that time. Submit an initial report and update it as the investigation progresses. Late reports are a contractual violation regardless of incident severity.',
    sourceRef: 'DFARS 252.204-7012(c); NIST SP 800-171 Rev 2 §3.6.2',
