    explanation: 'AC.L2-3.1.9 requires providing privacy and security notices consistent with CUI rules before users access the system. This is typically implemented as a login banner that informs users that: the system is for authorized use only, activities may be monitored, use constitutes consent to monitoring, and unauthorized use is subject to consequences. The notice must appear before login is complete — not just in an employee handbook or onboarding materials.',
    mindsetNote: 'The login banner is one of the first things an assessor checks. It is straightforward to implement and easy to verify. Absence of a banner is a finding against AC.L2-3.1.9. The content matters: a banner that just says "Welcome to the company portal" does not satisfy the practice. Look for explicit language about authorized use, monitoring consent, and consequences of misuse.',
