    explanation: 'SC.L2-3.13.10 requires establishing and managing cryptographic keys — management encompasses the entire key lifecycle: generation (using approved methods/tools), storage (keys must be protected with at minimum equivalent security to the data they protect — storing keys alongside encrypted files defeats the purpose), distribution, use, rotation, and destruction. All three practices described are findings: (1) an unvetted online tool may not use approved RNG or key sizes; (2) co-locating keys with encrypted data means anyone who accesses the files can also access the key; (3) no rotation means a compromised key grants indefinite access to historical CUI.',
    mindsetNote: 'Key management is a lifecycle discipline. When assessing SC.L2-3.13.10, walk through each phase: How were the keys generated? Are they stored separately and protected? Who has access? When are they rotated? What is the key compromise procedure? A contractor who has implemented encryption but cannot answer these questions has encryption theater, not real protection.',
