    explanation: 'SC.L2-3.13.15 requires protecting the authenticity of communications sessions. Cookie security attributes are direct session protection controls: Secure prevents transmission over unencrypted connections (token sniffing), HttpOnly prevents JavaScript access to the cookie (XSS-based token theft), SameSite prevents cross-origin requests from carrying the cookie (CSRF attacks). Missing any of these creates attack vectors that allow an adversary to steal or forge the session, impersonating an authenticated user without defeating the original authentication. While SC.L2-3.13.8 covers data-in-transit encryption broadly, 3.13.15 specifically targets session integrity and authenticity.',
    mindsetNote: 'Session security is a web application implementation detail that assessors often overlook in favor of infrastructure controls. SC.L2-3.13.15 pulls web application session management into scope. When evaluating CUI web portals, assessors should inspect cookie attributes using browser developer tools, check for session fixation vulnerabilities, and verify that session tokens are rotated after authentication. These are development-time decisions with run-time impact.',
