    explanation: 'A FedRAMP Moderate authorized cloud service can provide strong evidence for controls that the cloud provider implements — infrastructure security, physical security, availability controls, and some audit and configuration management functions. However, CMMC practices have both a provider-side and a customer-side responsibility. Access control (who can access the CUI in the cloud), audit log review (does the OSC review the logs?), incident response (does the OSC have an IR process for cloud-hosted CUI incidents?), and configuration management of the OSC\'s own cloud environment are OSC responsibilities that FedRAMP authorization does not satisfy. The assessor must evaluate both what the cloud provider implements (using FedRAMP documentation as evidence) and what the OSC implements as its portion of the shared responsibility model.',
    mindsetNote: 'Cloud shared responsibility is one of the most nuanced areas in CMMC assessment. The rule of thumb: FedRAMP authorization is evidence, not a blanket waiver. For each practice, ask "which part of this is the cloud provider responsible for, and which part is the OSC responsible for?" Physical security of the data center is entirely the provider\'s responsibility. Ensuring only authorized users can access CUI in the cloud is entirely the OSC\'s responsibility. Most practices have both layers. A FedRAMP package helps the assessment but never eliminates OSC obligations.',
    sourceRef: 'CMMC Scoping Guide Level 2 v2.0 §4; CMMC Assessment Guide Level 2 v2.0 §1.2; FedRAMP Authorization Act (NDAA FY23)',
