    explanation: 'Under 32 CFR Part 170.21, closing POA&M items requires a follow-on C3PAO assessment that evaluates the remediated practices using the same examine/interview/test methods as the original assessment. The OSC cannot self-attest closure of a conditional certification POA&M — that would defeat the purpose of third-party assessment. The Lead Assessor cannot administratively close items based on documentation review alone; the full assessment process applies. The Cyber AB does not review individual POA&M closures. This has a practical scheduling implication: the OSC must schedule and complete a follow-on assessment before day 180, not simply remediate by day 180. A follow-on assessment takes time to schedule — OSCs who wait until day 160 to begin remediation may not have enough time.',
    mindsetNote: 'The 180-day clock runs to verified closure, not to remediation completion. This distinction matters enormously in practice. An OSC who finishes implementing controls on day 175 cannot close their POA&M in time if a C3PAO needs two weeks to schedule a follow-on visit. Practitioners should advise OSCs to complete remediation by day 120 at the latest to allow adequate time for the follow-on assessment cycle.',
    sourceRef: '32 CFR Part 170.21(c); CMMC Assessment Guide Level 2 v2.0 §3',
